<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-952-264  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 952 264.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Dec 9 1989 v139 p18(N) p32(L) 16 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computers speed up Post Office service. (Consumer's World Pages)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Postal service is automating its customer service throughthe use of computer terminals that weigh and calculate postalcosts of packages, automatic teller machines that sell stamps andcomputerized self service centers.andP;  About 54,000 computerterminals are installed at postal clerk stations and the PostOffice estimates all clerks will have the terminals by the end of1990.andP;  The terminals, called Integrated Retail Terminals, arewelcomed by the clerks, who claim the speed of the computers helpscut down customer lines.andP;  The self-service centers, calledInfopost and Autopost, are currently in test sites.andP;  Thesemachines answer customer questions, assign postal rates toparcels, sell stamps and speak in English and Spanish.andP;  Newself-adhesive postage stamps are being sold through automaticteller machines in another Post Office automation experiment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Postal ServiceAutomationPostal serviceGovernment Agency.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>